				<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body" aria-labelledby="firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-container>
					<div class="vector-body-before-content">
							<div class="mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id="contentSub"><div id="mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
					
					
					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Board with an alternating square pattern on which games are played</div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Chess.board.fabric.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Chess.board.fabric.png/250px-Chess.board.fabric.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="254" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Chess.board.fabric.png/500px-Chess.board.fabric.png 1.5x" data-file-width="1044" data-file-height="1059"></a><figcaption>A checkerboard</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>checkerboard</b> (<a href="/wiki/American_English" title="American English">American English</a>) or <b>chequerboard</b> (<a href="/wiki/British_English" title="British English">British English</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/Game_board" title="Game board">game board</a> of <a href="/wiki/Check_(pattern)" title="Check (pattern)">checkered</a> pattern on which <a href="/wiki/Checkers" title="Checkers">checkers</a> (also known as <a href="/wiki/English_draughts" title="English draughts">English draughts</a>) is played.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Most commonly, it consists of 64 squares (8×8) of alternating dark and light color, typically green and <a href="/wiki/Buff_(colour)" title="Buff (colour)">buff</a> (official tournaments), black and red (consumer commercial), or black and white (printed diagrams). An 8×8 checkerboard is used to play many other games, including <a href="/wiki/Chess" title="Chess">chess</a>, whereby it is known as a <a href="/wiki/Chessboard" title="Chessboard">chessboard</a>. Other rectangular square-tiled boards are also often called checkerboards. In The Netherlands, however, a <i>dambord</i> (checker board) has 10 rows and 10 columns for 100 squares in total (see article International draughts).
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Games_and_puzzles_using_checkerboards">Games and puzzles using checkerboards</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Checkerboard&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Games and puzzles using checkerboards"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Childrens_Museum_of_Indianapolis_-_Checkers.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/The_Childrens_Museum_of_Indianapolis_-_Checkers.jpg/250px-The_Childrens_Museum_of_Indianapolis_-_Checkers.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="188" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/The_Childrens_Museum_of_Indianapolis_-_Checkers.jpg/500px-The_Childrens_Museum_of_Indianapolis_-_Checkers.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600"></a><figcaption>A game of checkers within the permanent collection of <a href="/wiki/The_Children%27s_Museum_of_Indianapolis" title="The Children's Museum of Indianapolis">The Children's Museum of Indianapolis</a></figcaption></figure>
<p><a href="/wiki/Martin_Gardner" title="Martin Gardner">Martin Gardner</a> featured puzzles based on checkerboards in his November 1962 <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_Games_column" class="mw-redirect" title="Mathematical Games column">Mathematical Games column</a> in Scientific American. A square checkerboard with an alternating pattern is used for games including:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Amazons_(game)" class="mw-redirect" title="Amazons (game)">Amazons</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chapayev_(game)" title="Chapayev (game)">Chapayev</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chess" title="Chess">Chess</a> and some of its <a href="/wiki/Chess_variant" title="Chess variant">variants</a> (see <a href="/wiki/Chessboard" title="Chessboard">chessboard</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Czech_draughts" title="Czech draughts">Czech draughts</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Draughts" class="mw-redirect" title="Draughts">Draughts</a>, also known as checkers</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Fox_games" title="Fox games">Fox games</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Frisian_draughts" title="Frisian draughts">Frisian draughts</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Gounki" title="Gounki">Gounki</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/International_draughts" title="International draughts">International draughts</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Italian_draughts" title="Italian draughts">Italian draughts</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lines_of_Action" title="Lines of Action">Lines of Action</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pool_checkers" class="mw-redirect" title="Pool checkers">Pool checkers</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Russian_checkers" class="mw-redirect" title="Russian checkers">Russian checkers</a></li></ul>
<p>The following games require an 8×8 board and are sometimes played on a <a href="/wiki/Chessboard" title="Chessboard">chessboard</a>.
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Arimaa" title="Arimaa">Arimaa</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Breakthrough_(board_game)" title="Breakthrough (board game)">Breakthrough</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Crossings_(game)" title="Crossings (game)">Crossings</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mak-yek" title="Mak-yek">Mak-yek</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Makruk" title="Makruk">Makruk</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Martian_Chess" class="mw-redirect" title="Martian Chess">Martian Chess</a></li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Gallery">Gallery</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Checkerboard&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Gallery"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-nolines">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 205px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 200px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Empty_wooden_chessboard.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="An empty 8×8 checkerboard"><img alt="An empty 8×8 checkerboard" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Empty_wooden_chessboard.jpg/250px-Empty_wooden_chessboard.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Empty_wooden_chessboard.jpg/330px-Empty_wooden_chessboard.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1920" data-file-height="1440"></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">An empty 8×8 checkerboard</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 205px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 200px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Font_Awesome_5_solid_chess-board.svg" class="mw-file-description" title="An empty 8×8 checkerboard diagram"><img alt="An empty 8×8 checkerboard diagram" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Font_Awesome_5_solid_chess-board.svg/120px-Font_Awesome_5_solid_chess-board.svg.png" decoding="async" width="120" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Font_Awesome_5_solid_chess-board.svg/250px-Font_Awesome_5_solid_chess-board.svg.png 1.5x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512"></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">An empty 8×8 checkerboard diagram</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 205px">
